javax.microedition.sensor
Class SensorProtocolPermission

java.lang.Object
  java.security.Permission
      javax.microedition.io.GCFPermission
          javax.microedition.sensor.SensorProtocolPermission
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.security.Guard
public final class SensorProtocolPermission
extends javax.microedition.io.GCFPermission

This class represents an access right to a connection/connections via the "sensor" protocol. The SensorProtocolPermission grants the permission to either sensors measuring a certain quantity or to private/protected sensors. If the name given is a sensor URI then the access for sensors pointed by this URI is granted. Because a valid sensor URI always contains a quantity, SensorProtocolPermissions constructed with a URI will always address sensors of one quantity. The sensor URI is defined in SensorConnection.

PRIVATE and PROTECTED constants are for private and protected sensors; the access is granted for the whole group of such sensors. The sensors of the group are most probably measuring different quantities. If a sensor happens to be both private and protected the permission has to be requested by the sensor URL.

Permission class with different name options

Named permission

Methods protected by this permission

SensorProtocolPermission(PRIVATE) javax.microedition.sensor.PrivateSensor, javax.microedition.io.Connector.sensor Connector.open() , PushRegistry.registerConnection()
SensorProtocolPermission(PROTECTED) javax.microedition.sensor.ProtectedSensor, javax.microedition.io.Connector.sensor Connector.open() , PushRegistry.registerConnection()
SensorProtocolPermission(sensor_url) javax.microedition.io.Connector.sensor

If needed also

javax.microedition.sensor.PrivateSensor and/or javax.microedition.sensor.ProtectedSensor

Connector.open(), PushRegistry.registerConnection()

In the Mobile Sensor API the only security control points are opening a connection and registering for push, no other methods are protected. That is why no actions are listed here.

Note: the sensor URI as a name may refer to a single sensor or to multiple sensors, including private and protected sensors. If the policy prevents opening any of these sensors, the permission must not be granted.

implies

public boolean implies(java.security.Permission p)

The method checks if this SensorProtocolPermission object "implies" the specified permission. More specifically, this method returns true if:

  • p is an instanceof SensorProtocolPermission, and
  • p's actions return null, and
  • p's name equals this object's name, or if
  • p's sensor URI defines a subset of the category (private/protected), or if
  • p's sensor URI defines a subset of sensors of this object's URI

Specified by:
implies in class java.security.Permission
Parameters:
p - the permission to check against.
Returns:
true if the specified permission is implied by this object, false if not.
